utual aid and collective healing. Through her brother’s experience with the criminal justice system, we see the trauma caused by policing practices and mass imprisonment, but we also witness family members finding strength as they come together to demand justice for their loved ones. And while her own challenges as a young mother reveal the vast inequities of our healthcare system, Benjamin also describes how the support of doulas and midwives can keep Black mothers and babies alive and well.Born of a stubborn hopefulness, Viral Justice offers a passionate, inspiring, and practical vision of how small changes can add up to large ones, transforming our relationships and communities, and helping us build a more just and joyful world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAbleism.  aAffordable housing.  aAlcoholism.  aAngus Deaton.  aAuburn University.  aBasic skills.  aBirth control.  aBlack Feminist Thought.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aBlack people.  aCT scan.  aCancer.  aCase study.  aChild care.  aChildbirth.  aCitizenship.  aClassroom.  aClinical trial.  aColonialism.  aCommunity land trust.  aContemporary slavery.  aCorrosion.  aCounterintelligence.  aCovid-19.  aCurriculum.  aEducation.  aEmotional Intelligence.  aEmployment.  aEric Garcetti.  aEugenics.  aFemininity.  aFlint River (Michigan).  aGeographer.  aGleaners.  aGlory hole (sexual slang).  aGrandad (Only Fools and Horses).  aGrandparent.  aGroup call.  aHarvard Law School.  aHate crime.  aHealth care.  aHealth equity.  aHousehold.  aHypocrisy.  aInfant.  aInnate intelligence.  aInstitution.  aJohnnetta B. Cole.  aJohnson Act.  aLand mine.  aMedical history.  aMemorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe.  aMidwife.  a